{{Infobox language |name=Sa‘īdi Arabic |states=[[Egypt]] |speakers=22.4 million |date=2016 |ref=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/aec|title=Arabic, Sa’idi Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref> |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Semitic languages|Semitic]] |fam3=[[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]] |fam4=[[Arabic languages|Arabic]] |fam5=Central |script=[[Arabic alphabet]] |iso3=aec |glotto=said1239 |glottorefname=Saidi Arabic |notice=IPA |lingua=12-AAC-eb<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linguasphere.info/lcontao/tl_files/pdf/index/LS_index_a-a.pdf |page=128 |title=a |work=The Linguasphere Register |accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref> }}
'''Ṣa‘īdi Arabic''' ({{lang-aec|صعيدي|links=no}}, <small>locally</small> {{IPA-arz|sˤɑˈʕiːdi|}}, {{IPA-arz|sˤeˈʕiːdi|lang|link=yes}}), also known as '''Upper Egyptian Arabic''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/language/aec |title=Arabic, Sa’idi Spoken |work=[[Ethnologue]] |accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref> is a variety of [[Arabic]] spoken by the [[Sa'idi people|Ṣa‘īdi people]] south of [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], to the border of [[Sudan]].<ref>Versteegh, p. 163</ref> It shares linguistic features with both [[Egyptian Arabic]] and the [[Quran]]'s [[Classical Arabic]]. Dialects include Middle and Upper Egyptian Arabic.
Speakers of Egyptian Arabic do not always understand more [[conservative (language)|conservative varieties]] of Ṣa‘īdi Arabic.<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>
Ṣa‘īdi Arabic carries little [[prestige (sociolinguistics)|prestige]] nationally, but it continues to be widely spoken, including in the north by rural migrants who have partially adapted to Egyptian Arabic. For example, the Ṣa‘īdi [[genitive case|genitive]] [[exponent (linguistics)|exponent]] is usually replaced with Egyptian ''bitāʿ'', but the realisation of {{IPAslink|q}} as {{IPAblink|ɡ}} is retained (normally realised in Egyptian Arabic as {{IPAblink|ʔ}}).
Second- and third-generation Ṣa‘īdi migrants are [[monolingual]] in Egyptian Arabic but maintain cultural and family ties to the south.
The Egyptian poet [[Abdel Rahman el-Abnudi]] wrote in his native Sa'idi.
